n practices, to fashion new systems of belief. From Vodou, Santería, Regla de Palo, the Abakuá Secret Society, and Obeah to Quimbois and Espiritismo, the volume traces the historical–cultural origins of the major Creole religions, as well as the newer traditions such as Rastafari.This third edition updates the scholarship by featuring new critical approaches that have been brought to bear on the study of religion, such as queer studies, environmental studies, and diasporic studies. The third edition also expands the regional considerations of the diaspora to the US Latinx communities that are influenced by Creole spiritual practices, taking into account the increased significance of material culture?art, music, literature, and healing practices influenced by Creole religions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aAfro-Caribbean cults. 7aRELIGION / Ethnic & Tribal.2bisacsh  aAbakua’.  aAllan Kardec.  aBrujeria.  aCaribbean religion.  aCaribbean.  aCentro Espiritista.  aColonization.  aColony.  aCongas.  aCreole.  aCreolization.  aCurandera.  aDespojo.  aDiaspora.  aDivination.  aDowtah.  aDreads.  aDuppies.  aEspiritismo.  aExtinction.  aExtractive practices.  aGanja.  aHaile Selassie.  aHerbalism.  aHounfort.  aHoungan.  aHybridity.  aI-tal.  aInitiation.  aJah.  aKanzo.  aLivity.  aLwa.  aLydia Cabrera.  aManbo.  aMaroon Communities.  aMedium.  aMining.  aMulticulturalism.  aNatural History.  aNganga.  aNyabinghi.  aObeahman.  aOrisha practices.  aOrisha.  aPalo.  aPlantation.  aQuimboiseur.  aReggae.  aRegla de Ocha.  aReligion.  aSanteria.  aSantería.  aServiteur.  aShaker rituals.  aShango.  aSlavery.  aSpirit bath.  aSpirit possession.  aSyncretism.  aVodou.  aYoruba.  aZombie.1 aMurphy, Jose